Section section_02 (Chars 9138–12778):
Section Summary: In his later years, Herbert Spencer was disheartened to see that his social and political doctrines were not widely accepted by a new generation of thinkers. Despite this, his contributions to the philosophy of life and mind remain significant. Spencer's philosophy emphasized the concept of evolution as a universal principle, governed by natural laws and processes, which he believed could explain all phenomena, including the growth of society and individual life. He proposed a sweeping formula that embodied the fundamental traits of evolution, and his philosophy dealt with concepts such as causation, force, and motion. Ultimately, Spencer's philosophy aimed to interpret all phenomena in terms of matter, motion, and force, and to unify knowledge by explaining everything in terms of these fundamental principles.
